Description:
Discovered as a mechanism of tissue quality control, cell&nbsp;competition influences tissue colonisation in homeostasis and during tumorigenesis.&nbsp;This symposium will highlight several aspects of the tumorigenesis process that&nbsp;are influenced by cell competition. In early tumorigenesis cell competition&nbsp;acts both as a tumour suppressive factor, eliminating transformed cells, and as&nbsp;a tumour promoting force, highjacked by cells that acquire oncogenic&nbsp;mutations,&nbsp;such as mutations in p53 or Apc. Tumour heterogeneity can lead to intratumor&nbsp;cell competition and drive the dissemination of locally less dominant clones. As&nbsp;such, metastasis is not necessarily driven by&nbsp;dominant clone but could be&nbsp;driven by a non-dominant loser clone within the primary tumor.&nbsp;Clonal cooperation&nbsp;instead is emerging as a strategy for transformed cells to evade their out-competition&nbsp;by non-tumour&nbsp;neighbours. Throughout, we will discuss current insights into the&nbsp;mechanisms of cell competition and how these can be leveraged as therapeutic&nbsp;opportunities in cancer.<br />
